ᾗ 12. The praetor's edicts and orders seem, like the leges (Dion. Halic. R. A. 3. 36), to have been engraved on tablets of oak, which were then whitened over and exposed to public view. Subsequently other materials were used: ‘in albu, vel in charta, vel in alia materia’ Dig. 2. 1. 7. pr., but the name album was retained. Albi corruptio is used in a wide sense: ‘is qui album raserit, corruperit, sustulerit, mutaverit, quidve aliud propositum edicendi causa turbaverit, extra ordinem punietur’ Paul. sent. rec. 1. 13a. 3. For the action of a patron against his freed· man sor suing him without first obtaining the praetor's permission (Tit. 16. 3 ins.) see Gaius iv. 46, which also refers to the penal aetio in factum ‘contra eum qui vi exemerit eum qui in ius vocatur : ' for the latter cf. also Dig. 2. 7.
